Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth US president in history.
The diploma, medal and check for $1.4 million will be given to them, among other things, for their outstanding efforts in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning and will have a lot to do.
First, visit to the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee which, in October, elected him among 172 people and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple are then scheduled to meet King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, though the third to receive it in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, he will speak about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this subject, knowing that he is receiving the award as the president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts were further increased with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which not forgetting to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the cheque of ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kronor).
He's proposing to donate them to charity, but he hasn't decided yet to which organization.
During the entire programme, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the award.
He mentioned, for example, feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He also said that the prize was not just for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
