U.S.A.: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, like a diligent student repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it turned out to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "just like in Iraq" used several times in the same text, but he also used the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward".
It was he himself who three years ago criticised Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from the civil war, and he called it "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences".
The next few months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no mention of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but objectively left his successor a much more favorable starting position than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes to repeat the miracle.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, most notably the Afghan operation commander-in-chief General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subordinate relationships, subjected the undecided gunners in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to help him.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he fooled the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had previously counted at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his goal to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this process in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the Iraq procedure.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being honoured.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to change the chief every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, though formally established, will remain only a Potemkin people.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to the confusing relationships, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even setting a state that is "action-ready", a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is shocked by his willingness.
For the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now on the verge of exploding.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the soldiers sent to war to "return home soon", will work some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, and they do not want to explain to their electors, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war on the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, which could radically affect the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
The answers will have to be sought precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic turnaround for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential elections are three years away and that is why there is still a lot of time to find another strategy, if this one proves a total failure.
The executives of Goldman Sachs bank will no longer receive cash bonuses
The top executives of the American bank Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
The entity announced it to react to the harsh criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 senior executives will receive, instead of money, shares that cannot be sold within a minimum period of five years.
In addition, the shares may be withdrawn if they have assumed excessive risks.
