The unionists in their declaration of the emergency strike of Monday, also demanded that none of the employees, who last Wednesday interrupted the manufacture, were penalized in any way.
As far as overtime is concerned, the unions demand that the company keep it to a minimum.
In addition, this year they demand for this work a remuneration of 5,000 crowns.
The automobile factory in Nošovice Hyundai currently has 2,000 employees.
Serial production was started last November.
Until last September it produced approximately 80,000 cars; its current production potential is 200,000 cars a year.
A Czech discovery: a substance effective even in 'cold' HIV viruses
Czech and German scientists test new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective on a common variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, patients' lives may be significantly prolonged by a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from replicating in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs will no longer work.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University demonstrates the possibility of mastering virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarbons have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is different from all the drugs used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, 'improved' compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus albumin.
Metal-carbonates have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no fractionation of HIV and no mature and infectious virus corpuscles would be created.
If HIV protease is stopped, the virus will also stop spreading in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still being modified systematically.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test for the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was carried out in test tubes, and also against its resistant variants obtained from HIV patients.
