Some readers will come to this new book as admirers of the author's latest work "Why the French Don't Like Headcarves" (2006), an elegant and thoroughly argued study of an issue that divided and preoccupied the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects are still felt today.
Mr. Bowen's latest book has a broader and more ambitious outlook.
As a good anthropologist, she wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now provide France's 5-6 million Muslims with what Mr. Bowen calls "Islamic spaces".
He is a good listener who plays back debates between teachers and students on the questions that interest them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should they teach young Muslims about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it legitimate for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane issues, he argues, things of daily life, that concern the media more than political dramas.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, professors and intellectuals, none of them of any repute, with the possible exception of Tariq Ramadan, an Arab Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
