It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by between 25 and 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would cut theirs during the same period by between 15 and 30 percent.
Together, the countries would cut emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred the talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated conversations over the past week.
US special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary cuts by major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
