For almost 300 years, the panel was part of the famous Borges family collection in Rome, then it appeared successively in the house of the French actress Cécile Sorel, as part of her bathtub in her private mansion in Paris, and in the house of Paul Raynaud, minister of the Third French Republic and President of the Council for a short time, before Marshal Pétain took power.
For about fifty years, his whereabouts were unknown.
Reviewing the Louvre Museum database, Florent Heintz discovered that this panel was part of an "Emile Zola succession" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the fresco of the "Rougon-Macquart".
