Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees adhering to "values" determined from above, as it was formerly a question of imposing on consumers products devised by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the centre of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies for market conquest... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to the preference factors of the customers is regularly repeated.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all intellectual functions in the enterprise, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI "requires proactive behavior and forward-looking thinking from all parties involved"; it requires a commitment from employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of authoritarian management.
We therefore call for a managerial revolution, which would consist in putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
The internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire carried out by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid that it is not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Lastly, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioural theory that the American "neuroscience" has recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media have widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuited to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the smooth running of modern enterprises implies adopting a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists in integrating into all business management reasoning or practice a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it is clearly presented as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifuntional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivation.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilisation factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their 'social performance' and relocate human resource management 'on the spot'.
In this way they create a favourable environment for the organised development of a strong and efficient business intelligence.
