The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a six-foot-long (2.0 m) and five-foot-tall (1.5 m) animal that ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this wouldn't have been anything special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It tells us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we've found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation, the remains of five specimens were found.
A discovery confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found".
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, such as those also possessed by the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to air sacs, the birds' breathing is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the earliest and most primitive air-bag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lines separated at an early stage and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
All three cannot be descended from a single related ancestor, argue the researchers.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted picture, because in South America alone many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to be discovered.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral lineage of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a puzzle.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs spread across the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary into the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction in which the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat their opponents in the area.
Success stories don't always have a lifetime.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species that had also evolved in the Triassic and had since then led a miserable existence: the mammals.
