However, one who experiences dreamlike states during wakefulness, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be insane or a drug addict, or at least a maniac.
But such images and voices are not limited to the mentally ill or to drug addicts.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels, sometimes blur the lines between dream, madness, and reality.
Dream-modified states of conscious awareness can appear in a variety of forms, at best we call them visions, at worst, madness.
