Dreamlike hallucinations are almost as complex and detailed as dreams, which the person experiencing them believes to be real and which he subsequently cannot distinguish from waking.
Dream states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or illness, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened with a loss of self or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of one's own and imaginary that is uncoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a change of world occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an intolerable situation in itself that our own creative capacity allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
It's all real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old when his consciousness embarked on a journey of several days following a heart valve operation, including a heart transplant, while his body was condemned to immobility in the intensive care ward.
Claussen immersed himself in a world of his own making and visited strange places from other times: he found himself bedridden, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
You see it in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so he describes his experience.
In contrast, memories of the mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense than even real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, daydreaming, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of the outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Every modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
