75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed in the study 'Fecundidad y trayectoria laboral de las mujeres en España', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the start of cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they do.
Women who are not active outside the home, who work part-time or have a job with a fixed schedule, are more likely to start living together earlier, to have their first child earlier and to have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood and have fewer children.
"Women between 35 and 49 years old with a steady job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting to live together, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with steady jobs have needed more time of their life to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a great influence on maternity, but less on the mating calendar", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women at marriage and at the time of the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age at which they get married and have their first child.
The difference also persists between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education became mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"A further division is made between women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with intermediate or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child", Delgado said.
