Emergency brake assistance is now mandatory
As with anti-lock brakes and ESP, emergency braking systems will have to be a mandatory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a grace period is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, but, due to its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions due to reach.
The emergency braking assistant is what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the pedal that the driver gives.
But this one doesn't always hold that pressure to the end.
According to a study by the car manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not yet applied the brakes before the collision, and half of them had not used their full strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The assistance intervention, on the other hand, puts the braking system under maximum strain, reducing the distance the car takes to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such devices, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with injury to persons could be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, help by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
In the event of failure to react, even if the collision is unavoidable, the device shall exert maximum effort on the brakes to minimise damage.
